To convert markdown to HTML in C++, you can use a library called "libcmark" which is a C implementation of the CommonMark Markdown parser and renderer. Here is an example code snippet demonstrating how you can use the libcmark library to convert markdown to HTML:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <cmark-gfm.h> // Include the libcmark library header

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    // Parse the markdown input
    const char* result = cmark_markdown_to_html(markdown.c_str(), markdown.length(), CMARK_OPT_DEFAULT);

    // Convert the result to a string
    return std::string(result);
}

int main() {
    // Markdown input
    std::string markdown = "# Hello, World!\nThis is **bold** text.";

    // Convert markdown to HTML
    std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);

    // Output the HTML result
    std::cout << "HTML output:\n" << html << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

In this code snippet, we include the necessary headers and define a function `markdownToHtml` that takes a markdown string as input, uses the `cmark_markdown_to_html` function provided by the libcmark library to convert the markdown to HTML, and returns the resulting HTML string.

You can compile and run this code by linking against the libcmark library. The library provides various options for customizing the Markdown to HTML conversion process, and you can refer to the libcmark documentation for more details on how to use them.

In TypeScript, you can specify multiple possible types for a value by using union types. You can do this by separating the types with a vertical bar "|". For example, if you wanted a value that could be either a string or a number, you would define it like this:

```typescript
let myValue: string | number;
```

To ensure that only one type is actually used in practice, you can use type guards or type assertions to narrow down the type of the value. 

Type guards are conditional statements that check the type of a value at runtime and narrow down the possible types. Here is an example using a type guard to check if the value is a string:

```typescript
function isString(value: string | number): value is string {
    return typeof value === 'string';
}

let myValue: string | number = "hello";

if (isString(myValue)) {
    // Here myValue is treated as a string
    console.log(myValue.toUpperCase());
} else {
    // Here myValue is treated as a number
    console.log(myValue.toFixed(2));
}
```

Type assertions allow you to explicitly tell the TypeScript compiler that you know more about the type of a value than it does. You can use the "as" keyword to assert the type of a value. Here is an example using a type assertion to treat the value as a string:

```typescript
let myValue: string | number = "hello";

let myString: string = myValue as string;
console.log(myString.toUpperCase());
```

By using type guards or type assertions, you can ensure that only one type is actually used in practice when working with values that have multiple possible types in TypeScript.

In LaTeX, you can automatically generate a table of contents using the `\tableofcontents` command. This command should be placed in your document where you want the table of contents to appear.

To get an accurate table of contents, you typically need to compile your LaTeX document twice. This is because LaTeX needs to gather information about the sections and subsections in your document in the first run, and then generates the table of contents in the second run.

Here is an example:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section.

\section{Methods}
This is the methods section.

\subsection{Experimental Setup}
Details about the experimental setup.

\end{document}
```

When you compile this document with LaTeX, the table of contents will be automatically generated, listing the sections and subsections in your document with their corresponding page numbers.
